---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Clock Error and Its Effect on Positioning">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/timing">Timing</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>Clock Error</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Timing · Article 4 of 5</span>
        <h1>Clock Error and Its Effect on Positioning</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          A 1-nanosecond clock error causes 30 centimetres of ranging error. A 1-microsecond
          error causes 300 metres. Clock errors — in the receiver, in the satellite, and in
          the relativistic corrections — are woven through every GNSS measurement. This article
          explains each type, how it enters the observation equations, and how receivers deal with it.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>10 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#clock-range">Clock error and ranging error</a></li>
          <li><a href="#receiver-clock">Receiver clock error</a></li>
          <li><a href="#satellite-clock">Satellite clock error</a></li>
          <li><a href="#relativistic">Relativistic clock corrections</a></li>
          <li><a href="#fourth-unknown">The fourth unknown</a></li>
          <li><a href="#inter-system">Inter-system time offsets</a></li>
          <li><a href="#carrier-phase-clock">Clock error in carrier phase</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <h2 id="clock-range">Clock error and ranging error</h2>
      <p>GNSS measures distance by measuring time. The pseudorange is:</p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">rho = c x delta_t</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          rho = measured pseudorange (m) · c = 299,792,458 m/s · delta_t = signal travel time (s)<br/><br/>
          Because c is so large, tiny timing errors produce significant ranging errors.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="clock-sensitivity">
        <div class="cs-title">Clock error to ranging error</div>
        <div class="cs-rows">
          <div class="cs-row">
            <div class="cs-time">1 nanosecond (10⁻⁹ s)</div>
            <div class="cs-range cs-good">0.30 m</div>
            <div class="cs-context">Satellite clock residual after broadcast correction</div>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-row">
            <div class="cs-time">10 nanoseconds</div>
            <div class="cs-range cs-ok">3.0 m</div>
            <div class="cs-context">Typical timing receiver accuracy</div>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-row">
            <div class="cs-time">100 nanoseconds</div>
            <div class="cs-range cs-warn">30 m</div>
            <div class="cs-context">Rough receiver clock uncertainty at startup</div>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-row">
            <div class="cs-time">1 microsecond (10⁻⁶ s)</div>
            <div class="cs-range cs-bad">300 m</div>
            <div class="cs-context">Receiver clock after brief satellite loss</div>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-row">
            <div class="cs-time">1 millisecond (10⁻³ s)</div>
            <div class="cs-range cs-bad">300 km</div>
            <div class="cs-context">Catastrophic — prevents positioning</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 id="receiver-clock">Receiver clock error</h2>
      <p>
        Consumer and survey GNSS receivers use a <strong>quartz oscillator</strong> — cheap,
        compact and low-power, but far less stable than satellite atomic clocks.
        A typical receiver quartz drifts ~1 ms/day (~300 km/day of ranging error if uncorrected).
        The receiver clock offset c·delta_t_r appears identically in all pseudoranges at the
        same epoch — it is a common bias that must be solved as the fourth unknown.
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">rho_i = r_i + c·delta_t_r - c·delta_t^s_i + I_i + T_i + epsilon_i</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          r_i = true geometric range (m) · c·delta_t_r = receiver clock (same for all satellites)<br/>
          c·delta_t^s_i = satellite clock (corrected by nav message) · I = iono · T = tropo<br/><br/>
          c·delta_t_r is identical for all n observations. It cannot be separated from position
          using a single observation — with n &ge; 4 it becomes the fourth unknown.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="clock-models">
        <div class="cm-card">
          <div class="cm-title">White noise (reset each epoch)</div>
          <div class="cm-desc">Clock offset estimated fresh every epoch — no prediction forward. Suitable for consumer oscillators where drift is large and unpredictable.</div>
          <div class="cm-use">Used by: most consumer and low-cost receivers</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cm-card cm-rw">
          <div class="cm-title">Random walk (carried forward)</div>
          <div class="cm-desc">Clock modelled as random walk: delta_t_r(k) = delta_t_r(k-1) + w_k. Allows clock aiding — filter maintains estimate even with fewer than 4 satellites visible.</div>
          <div class="cm-use">Used by: precision timing and survey receivers with TCXO/OCXO</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 id="satellite-clock">Satellite clock error</h2>
      <p>
        Despite being atomic clocks, satellite oscillators drift relative to GNSS system time.
        This drift is monitored by the ground control segment and broadcast as clock correction
        parameters in the navigation message:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">delta_t^s(t) = a0 + a1(t - t_oc) + a2(t - t_oc)²</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          a0 = clock bias (s) · a1 = frequency drift (s/s) · a2 = drift rate (s/s²)<br/>
          t_oc = reference epoch (seconds of GPS week)<br/><br/>
          After applying this correction, residual satellite clock error is typically &lt;1 m.
          IGS precise clock products reduce this to ~3 cm.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Relativistic periodic correction</h3>
      <p>
        A satellite in an elliptical orbit experiences varying gravitational potential and
        velocity, causing a periodic relativistic clock correction that must be applied in
        addition to the polynomial:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">delta_t_rel = F · e · sqrt(a) · sin(E_k)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          F = -4.442807633 × 10⁻¹⁰ s/√m · e = orbital eccentricity · a = semi-major axis (m)<br/>
          E_k = eccentric anomaly at time t<br/><br/>
          Magnitude: up to ±46 ns (±14 m) for typical GPS eccentricities of ~0.01.
          This correction is mandatory per IS-GPS-200. Omitting it introduces a periodic
          14 m ranging error with a ~12 hour period.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 id="relativistic">Relativistic clock corrections</h2>
      <p>Two relativistic effects act simultaneously on satellite clocks in opposite directions:</p>

      <div class="relativity-cards">
        <div class="rel-card rel-grav">
          <div class="rel-title">Gravitational time dilation</div>
          <div class="rel-effect">General relativity</div>
          <div class="rel-desc">
            Clocks run faster in weaker gravitational fields. A GPS satellite at 20,200 km
            is in weaker gravity than a ground clock — its atomic clock runs
            <strong>faster</strong> by approximately 45.9 µs/day.
          </div>
          <div class="rel-magnitude">+45.9 µs/day</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rel-card rel-vel">
          <div class="rel-title">Velocity time dilation</div>
          <div class="rel-effect">Special relativity</div>
          <div class="rel-desc">
            Moving clocks run slower. A GPS satellite moves at ~3.87 km/s in orbit,
            so its clock runs <strong>slower</strong> than a stationary ground clock by
            approximately 7.2 µs/day.
          </div>
          <div class="rel-magnitude">-7.2 µs/day</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="net-correction">
        <div class="nc-title">Net relativistic correction</div>
        <div class="nc-calc">+45.9 µs/day - 7.2 µs/day = +38.4 µs/day = 11.5 km/day of error</div>
        <div class="nc-desc">
          Without correction GPS clocks would gain 38.4 µs/day — equivalent to 11.5 km/day
          of position error. The correction is applied before launch by manufacturing satellite
          clocks to run at 10.22999999545 MHz instead of 10.23 MHz. Once in orbit the
          relativistic effects bring them back to the correct rate.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔬</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Relativity is not optional:</strong> IS-GPS-200 explicitly requires receivers
          to apply the periodic relativistic correction. The constant 38.4 µs/day offset is
          pre-corrected in satellite hardware. GNSS is the most prominent everyday engineering
          application of Einstein's theories of relativity.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 id="fourth-unknown">The fourth unknown</h2>
      <p>
        The receiver clock offset delta_t_r must be estimated simultaneously with position —
        this is why GNSS needs at least 4 satellites. With n &gt; 4, the overdetermined system
        is solved by weighted least squares.
      </p>
      <p>
        An important consequence: because delta_t_r is common to all observations, it cancels
        when differencing observations between two satellites at the same receiver:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">rho^i - rho^j = (r^i - r^j) - c·(delta_t^s_i - delta_t^s_j) + (I^i - I^j) + (T^i - T^j) + epsilon</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          The receiver clock term c·delta_t_r cancels exactly — it is the same for both satellites.
          This between-satellite single difference enables clock-free positioning and is used
          when fewer than 4 satellites are visible and the clock is carried from a previous epoch.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 id="inter-system">Inter-system time offsets</h2>
      <p>
        A multi-constellation receiver tracking GPS, Galileo, BeiDou and GLONASS simultaneously
        must estimate an additional Inter-System Bias (ISB) for each extra constellation,
        since each runs on a different time scale:
      </p>

      <div class="isb-table">
        <div class="isb-row isb-header">
          <span>Pair</span>
          <span>Name</span>
          <span>Nominal value</span>
          <span>Source</span>
        </div>
        <div class="isb-row">
          <span>GPS ↔ Galileo</span>
          <span>GGTO</span>
          <span>&lt;50 ns (nominally 0)</span>
          <span>Galileo nav message</span>
        </div>
        <div class="isb-row">
          <span>GPS ↔ BeiDou</span>
          <span>BGTO</span>
          <span>14 s (fixed)</span>
          <span>BeiDou nav message</span>
        </div>
        <div class="isb-row">
          <span>GPS ↔ GLONASS</span>
          <span>ISB</span>
          <span>~18 s + sub-µs residual</span>
          <span>Estimated in receiver filter</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        For GPS + Galileo + BeiDou + GLONASS, the navigation solution has 7 unknowns:
        (x, y, z, delta_t_GPS, ISB_GAL, ISB_BDS, ISB_GLO). This requires at least
        7 satellites — or fewer if ISBs are known from navigation messages.
      </p>

      <h2 id="carrier-phase-clock">Clock error in carrier phase</h2>
      <p>
        Carrier phase observations contain the same clock error as pseudoranges — just expressed
        in cycles (f·delta_t) rather than metres. For GPS L1 at 1575.42 MHz, 1 ns of clock
        error = 1.575 cycles = 0.30 m, identical to the pseudorange sensitivity.
      </p>
      <p>
        In double-differenced RTK processing, both clock errors vanish:
      </p>

      <div class="differencing-summary">
        <div class="ds-row">
          <div class="ds-op">Raw phase</div>
          <div class="ds-terms">
            <span class="ds-t keep">range</span>
            <span class="ds-t keep">N</span>
            <span class="ds-t cancel">rx clock</span>
            <span class="ds-t cancel">sv clock</span>
            <span class="ds-t keep">iono</span>
            <span class="ds-t keep">tropo</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ds-row">
          <div class="ds-op">Single diff (between receivers)</div>
          <div class="ds-terms">
            <span class="ds-t keep">delta-range</span>
            <span class="ds-t keep">delta-N</span>
            <span class="ds-t keep">rx clock diff</span>
            <span class="ds-t gone">sv clock ✓</span>
            <span class="ds-t small">delta-I</span>
            <span class="ds-t small">delta-T</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ds-row ds-highlight">
          <div class="ds-op">Double diff</div>
          <div class="ds-terms">
            <span class="ds-t keep">nabla-range</span>
            <span class="ds-t keep">nabla-N</span>
            <span class="ds-t gone">rx clock ✓</span>
            <span class="ds-t gone">sv clock ✓</span>
            <span class="ds-t small">nabla-I</span>
            <span class="ds-t small">nabla-T</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⏱️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">1 ns = 30 cm</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Clock error converts to ranging error at the speed of light. Satellite clock residuals (~1 ns) contribute ~30 cm. Receiver clock errors are much larger but solved as the fourth unknown.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🛰️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Satellite clock polynomial</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Broadcast a0, a1, a2 corrects satellite drift to &lt;1 m. IGS precise clocks achieve ~3 cm. The periodic relativistic correction (±14 m peak) is mandatory per IS-GPS-200.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌌</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Relativity: +38.4 µs/day</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Gravity speeds clocks (+45.9 µs/day), velocity slows them (-7.2 µs/day). Net 38.4 µs/day = 11.5 km/day error without correction. Pre-corrected in satellite hardware before launch.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">➖</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Double-differencing eliminates both</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Single difference cancels satellite clock. Second difference cancels receiver clock. RTK removes both simultaneously — leaving only atmospheric residuals and noise.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/timing/timing-applications" class="nav-prev">← Timing Applications</a>
        <a href="/learn/timing/pps-output" class="nav-next">PPS Output →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>IS-GPS-200N — GPS Interface Specification, Section 20.3.3.3.3 (relativistic correction). <a href="https://www.navcen.uscg.gov/sites/default/files/pdf/gps/IS-GPS-200N.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NAVCEN →</a></li>
          <li>Ashby, N. (2003). Relativity in the Global Positioning System. <em>Living Reviews in Relativity</em>, 6(1). <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.12942/lrr-2003-1" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Springer →</a></li>
          <li>Kaplan, E. D. & Hegarty, C. J. (2017). <em>Understanding GPS/GNSS: Principles and Applications</em>, 3rd ed. Artech House. Chapter 7.</li>
          <li>Teunissen, P. J. G. & Montenbruck, O. (eds.) (2017). <em>Springer Handbook of Global Navigation Satellite Systems</em>. Chapter 10.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learn-container { max-width: 820px; }
  .breadcrumb { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--text2); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(24px, 4vw, 38px); font-weight: 700; margin: 10px 0 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
  h2 { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; margin: 40px 0 16px; padding-top: 8px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  h3 { font-size: 17px; font-weight: 600; margin: 28px 0 12px; }
  .lead { font-size: 17px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 12px; max-width: 720px; }
  .article-meta { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); display: flex; gap: 8px; }
  p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  ul { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; padding-left: 24px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  li { margin-bottom: 6px; }
  strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }
  a { color: var(--accent2); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }

  .toc { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px 24px; margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .toc-title { font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .toc ol { margin: 0; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .toc li { font-size: 14px; }
  .toc a { color: var(--text2); text-decoration: none; }
  .toc a:hover { color: var(--accent); }

  .callout { display: flex; gap: 14px; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 24px 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; }
  .callout-icon { font-size: 18px; flex-shrink: 0; }
  .callout-info { background: rgba(0,153,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(0,153,255,0.18); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout strong { color: var(--text); }

  .formula-block { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-left: 3px solid var(--accent); border-radius: 8px; padding: 18px 20px; margin: 20px 0; overflow-x: auto; }
  .formula { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 13px; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 4px; line-height: 1.8; }
  .formula-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.7; margin-top: 10px; }

  .clock-sensitivity { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; overflow: hidden; margin: 20px 0; }
  .cs-title { font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); text-transform: uppercase; padding: 10px 14px; background: var(--bg3); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .cs-rows { display: flex; flex-direction: column; }
  .cs-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 200px 90px 1fr; gap: 12px; padding: 10px 14px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-size: 13px; align-items: center; }
  .cs-row:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .cs-time { font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--text2); }
  .cs-range { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 14px; font-weight: 700; }
  .cs-good { color: var(--accent); }
  .cs-ok { color: #a3e635; }
  .cs-warn { color: #fbbf24; }
  .cs-bad { color: #ff4757; }
  .cs-context { color: var(--text3); font-size: 12px; }

  .clock-models { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 14px; margin: 16px 0; }
  .cm-card { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 16px; }
  .cm-rw { border-color: rgba(0,212,170,0.3); }
  .cm-title { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .cm-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .cm-use { font-size: 11px; font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--text3); padding: 4px 8px; background: var(--bg3); border-radius: 4px; }

  .relativity-cards { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 14px; margin: 16px 0; }
  .rel-card { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 18px; }
  .rel-grav { border-top: 3px solid var(--accent); }
  .rel-vel  { border-top: 3px solid var(--accent2); }
  .rel-title { font-size: 15px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 4px; }
  .rel-effect { font-size: 11px; font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .rel-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .rel-magnitude { font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--accent); }

  .net-correction { background: rgba(0,212,170,0.05); border: 1px solid rgba(0,212,170,0.2); border-radius: 10px; padding: 18px 20px; margin: 16px 0; }
  .nc-title { font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .nc-calc { font-size: 15px; font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .nc-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.7; }

  .isb-table { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2px; margin: 16px 0; }
  .isb-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 150px 80px 160px 1fr; gap: 10px; padding: 10px 14px; background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 6px; font-size: 13px; align-items: center; }
  .isb-header { font-size: 10px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text3); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; font-family: var(--mono); background: var(--bg3); }
  .isb-row span:nth-child(2) { font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--accent); }

  .differencing-summary { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2px; margin: 16px 0; }
  .ds-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr; gap: 12px; padding: 10px 14px; background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 6px; align-items: center; }
  .ds-highlight { border-color: rgba(0,212,170,0.3); background: rgba(0,212,170,0.03); }
  .ds-op { font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); }
  .ds-terms { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 5px; }
  .ds-t { font-size: 11px; padding: 2px 7px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: var(--mono); }
  .keep { background: var(--bg3); color: var(--text2); }
  .cancel { background: rgba(255,71,87,0.1); color: #ff4757; }
  .gone { background: rgba(0,212,170,0.1); color: var(--accent); text-decoration: line-through; }
  .small { background: rgba(251,191,36,0.1); color: #fbbf24; }

  .summary-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); gap: 14px; margin: 24px 0; }
  .summary-card { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px; }
  .summary-icon { font-size: 22px; margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .summary-title { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .summary-body { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.6; }

  .nav-footer { display: flex; justify-content: space-between; margin: 48px 0 32px; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 12px; }
